er Using MOSFETs</h1>
<br>

<p>A CMOS inverter (NOT gate) is the simplest digital logic gate. It consists of two MOSFETs:</p>

<br>

<h3>Operating Principle</h3>

<table border=&quot;1&quot; cellpadding=&quot;6&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; width=&quot;50%&quot; >
    <tr>
        <th>Input</th>
        <th>PMOS</th>
        <th>NMOS</th>
        <th>Output</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>LOW (0 V)</td>
        <td>ON</td>
        <td>OFF</td>
        <td>VDD (Logic 1)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>HIGH (VDD)</td>
        <td>OFF</td>
        <td>ON</td>
        <td>GND (Logic 0)</td>
    </tr>
</table>"><h1>CMOS Inverter Using MOSFETs</h1>
<br>

<p>A CMOS inverter (NOT gate) is the simplest digital logic gate. It consists of two MOSFETs:</p>

<br>

<h3>Operating Principle</h3>

<table border="1" cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" width="50%">
    <tbody><tr>
        <th>Input</th>
        <th>PMOS</th>
        <th>NMOS</th>
        <th>Output</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>LOW (0 V)</td>
        <td>ON</td>
        <td>OFF</td>
        <td>VDD (Logic 1)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>HIGH (VDD)</td>
        <td>OFF</td>
        <td>ON</td>
        <td>GND (Logic 0)</td>
    </tr>
</tbody></table></div></foreignObject></g>